{"/service/ndnp/scu/batch_scu_flopeye_ver01/data/sn93067841/00295861757/1920111801/0336.xml":{"full_text":"(Hp (Hmrnty iiirrurii\nW. F. Tolley L. H. Cromer, Jr.\nPublishers.\nTHURSDAY, NOVEMBER 18, 1920.\nKINGSTREE NEEDS A HOTEL.'\nAt present Kingstree has no hotel.\nThe boarding houses of Kingstree\nare doing all they can to take care of\nour transient guests who find upon\narrival here that Kingstree affords\nNO hotel accommodations.\nWhat about the old Kellahan Hotel?\nWe are reliably informed that the\nboard of directors of the corporation\nthat recently purchased this property\nhave decided to \"hold it\"\nHold it for what?\nThe former owner held it, and\ncould have continued to hold it; but.\nhe doubtless said to himself, \"What's\nthe use? Kingstree needs a hotel, I\ndon't want to bother with it, and I'll\njust sell it to someone who will?and\nr: i 4.1. :n\ngive xuii^trec a iiutci mat v\\ 111 ki>*\nthe traveling public modern hotel accommodations.\"\nWell, he did sell, and sold out cheap.\nKinstreee needs a hotel and the\nonly thing to do is for the board of\ndirectors of the new project to get\nbusy and give Kingstree a hotel.\n\"Procrastination is the thief of\ntime.\" Time is money and money is\nhard to get now, we are told, but in\nthe face of this there is no excuse\nfor the directors or any one else laying\ndown on the job and finding satisfaction\nin the resolution to \"just\nhold it\" The former owner could\nhave done this.\nEvery day that Kingstree is without\na hotel, just that much farther is the\ntown of Kingstree shoved off the map.\nLet's get busy and have a hotel.\nIt is really as important to the town\naa a doctor.\nThe Signs of the Times.\nSigns are not wanting that the industrial\ncentres, and those who represent\nthem in the labor unions and\nin congress, are getting ready, to oppose\npolitically any effort to restrict\nthe importation of meats and foodstuffs\ninto the United States. Very\nwell. Let's go to the mat on that\nproposition; the sooner the better.\nWe called attention last week to\nthe fact that huge quantities of frozen\nlamb and mutton are being dumpted\nupon our markets, ^nd protested\nagainst the procedure. The laborites\nhave gone about the limit now in their\ninuilpnm> TVip v.Rr made them mas\nters of a temporary situation. Their\nsuccesses in forcing high wages, short\nhours and almost universal inefficiency\nhas turned their heads. They assume\nto dictate to the rest of the\nworld, and they are riding for a certain\nfalk They cannot put top-notch\nwages and cheap farm products over\nat one shot They would work eight\nhours a day for five days in a week\nat unheard-of pay, and have food and\nclothing doled out at prices involving\nthe poor devil who grew the grain\nthe live stock, the wool?and worked\nfrom twelve to sixteen hours a day\nfor six or seven days a week in loss! j\nIt can't be done. Labor has not yet\ngot its hand absolutely upon the\nthroat of production in these lines,\nand will so discover within the next\ntwelve months.\nThe \"Japs\" may not come in. The\nChinese may not come in. The employer\nmay not contract anywhere\nabroad for help to operate a farm olfactory.\nLabor is protected to the\nvery hilt When the farmer wants\nprotection, however, it is different\nCould selfishness find higher expression\nThe Gazette stands for American\nmarkets for American food products.\nIn the prosperity of the American\nfarmer lies the prosperity of every\nAmerican laborer, as well as merchant,\nmanufacturer or banker. If\nfarm products are costing consumers\ntoo much money it is not the fault of j\nthe farmer. If the consumer wants\nto know the real truth let him smoke\noat the small retailer everywhere.\nAnd in smoking him out let the expense\nand selling costs of the retailer\nbe scanned just to see how much his\nrent and his help are responsible for\nthe prices charged for the food purveyed.\nWhat figure does the carpenter,\nthe plumber, the bricklayer, the\nelectric light worker, the painter and\nplasterer cut in the matter of city\nrentals?\nThere is one thing sure; the average\nfarmer today, at present prices,\nia getting vastly less for his labor\nand his products than the wage-earners\nin town and city. One locomotive\nfreight engineer, for example, was\nearning over $400 per month before\nthe late raise in pay. He no doubt\nfavors free trade in wool and wheat\nand meat also. But he is not going\nto get it if American agriculture has\njeal friends in Washington.\nNo man likes to take a loss, but\nwe all have to do so at times. Profits\nare not reaped every year in any\nline of productivity of which we have\nknowledge. Except in war-time no one\ncan be guaranteed a profit in his business\noperations. The cost-plus prop orsition\nhas been an expensive luxury.\nIt forced production of millions of\ntons of war materials, good, bad and\nindifferent, which we are now paying\n/or in heavy taxation; but it cannot\nreasonably be expected to remain as\na settled policy either in government\nor private dealings.\nMoney has been lost on the downturn\nthat was inevitable after the\nexcesses of the great war by growers\n?i 1 i;\noi wneat unu growers 01 live slock.\nMen who would not sell corn last year\nat the market price then prevailing,\nbut held on for more, arc now compelled\nto take less. None of us takes\ndistasteful medicine without \"making\na face\" about it. It isn't picasant.\nBut, men and brethren, let's\nnot act too much like children, when\ndisappointments and discouragements\novertake us in our business. The\nfellow who grir.s under punishment\nis always more to be admired than\nhe who whines and talks about throwing\nup the sponge because he has\nbeen hit and hurt.\nThere is going to be a day of reck\noning in the existing situation, and a\nreturn to prosperity. The sun is going\nto shine upon American fanning\nand stockraising again. Make no\nmistake as to that. But the day of\nits return will be hastened quite as\nmuch by the exercise of patience,\nfaith and perseverance as by the\nthrowing of dynamite.?Breeder's Gazette.\nIn Memorium.\nHERBERT JAMES McCUTCHEN,\nwho died November 16, 1918.\nTwo sad, long years have passed\nSince that great sorrow fell;\nGone in his age of beauty,\nGone in his fairest bloom,\nBuried from us forever,\nDeep in the silent tomb.\nThe rose that is sweetest and fairest,\nIs the one that is killed by the frost;\nThe love that is sweetest and rarest\nIs the dear one I have lost.\nHe has left me sad and lonely,\nNot allowed to say good bye;\nBut I hope and trust to meet\nIn that land beyond the sky.\nOh, why was he taken\nSo young and so fair,\nWhen earth had so many\nIt better could spare.\nHard, hard was the blow\nThat compelled us to part\nFrom the loved ones so near\nAnd so dear to my heart\nSurrounded by friends, I am lonesome;\nIn the midst of my pleasure, I am\nblue,\nA smile on my face and a heart ache,\nLonging una yeanuug xux jruu.\nThere are two things death cannot\nsever:\nLove and memory?they live forever.\nDEVOTED WIFE.\no\nIn Memorium.\nMcCUTCHEN?In loving memory\nof my dear son, Herbert J. McCutchen,\nwho passed away on the evening\nof November 16, 1918.\nTwo sad years, with all its changes\n1 Cold Weatl\nI\nV/in ?f n OAmi\n1 CO, 1L a LU1U1\ntime to prepare fo\nand hard to get, b\nwarm at night wit!\nII BLANKETS At\nI We have a ni\nnew goods, direct\nI facturers, ranging\nI to $30.00. Thes\nreasonable for th\nI goods, but we ai\nthem, for a short1\nprices than they\nPhone or tell us\ndon't forget the r\nets for the little o\nSteele Furniti\nPhone 4 K1\nsj\nSince death strangely bade us part,\nBut, oh, dear Herbert, all its changes\nCannot take you from my heart.\nI often sit and think of you\nWhen I am all alone:\nFor memory is the only fiicnd\nThat grief can call its own.\nAnd when I kneel beside your tomb,\nFair flowers there I plant to bloom,\nI clasp my hands and whisper low,\nOh, dear, dear Herbert, I miss you\nso.\nMOTHER.\no\nWill some one at every Thanksgiving\ndinner in the county ask every\none present who has not joined the\nRed Cross to give his name and one\ndollar for the membership dues and\nthat one send the names and dollar*\ncollected to me that I may forward\nmembership certificates to the persons\nenrolling? Please, some one\nvolunteer and do this work about\nevery board of rejoicing on Thanksgiving\nday. I cannot help feeling\nthat if someone everywhere will do it,\nthere will be praise from highest\nHeaven and thanks from lowest earth.\nWM. W. BODDIE,\nRoll Call Chairman, Kingstree, S. C.\nThe New York Life Insurance Co.\nhas over three billion dollars insurance\nin force. Represented by R. D.\nMills. 9-23-tfc.\nIRENE CASTLE HAS\nFINE ROLE IN \"THE\nINVISIBLE BOND\"\nSophie Kerr's Novel, \"The See-Saw,\"\nTo Be Seen As Par amountArt\ncraft Picture.\nSophie Kerr's popular novel, \"The\nSee-Saw,\" which ran serially in a\nprominent magazine and wps later\npublished in book form, and has been\nadapted for the screen under the\ntitle of \"The Invisible Bond\" and is\nIrene Castles latest picture. It will\nbe shown at the Amuse-U-Thcatre,\nHemingway, S. C., Saturday, November\n20.\nThe story is about a husband and\nwife who are still in love after four|\nyears of married life. The husband,!\nhowever, believes that marriage j\nshould not curtail his personal liber-;\nty and prevent him from carrying onj\nan affair with a dashing young co- i\nquette. After the wife has endured\nmuch humiliation through her hus- j\nband's action, she divorces him and'\nhe speedily marries the other woman.'\nThe second wife holds the same the-!\noris about marriage as her husband,!\nand the tables are turned on him j\nwhen she soon begins courting the\ncompany of other men. A rich New\nj Yorker become infatuated with her,1\nand, furious because she will not re-|\nspond to his attentions, plunges them 1\nboth over a high cliff in a motor cari\nand kills himself and her. The hus-'\nband, getting the report^ of her death,\nthinks it is his first wife who has been\nkilled and rushes to her home, where\nthey are reconciled.\n\"The Invisible Bond\" was directed\nby Charles Maigne and is said to fur- j\n!nish Mrs. Castle with an opportunity\nto show quite remarkable talents as\nan emotional actress and also to wear\nj some attractive new gowns.\nier Coming! j\nng, and now is the 8\nr it. Coal is high |i\nut vou can keep I!\ni our I\nID COMFORTS\n_____\nce lot of Blankets,\nfrom the manuin\nprice from $2.50\ne prices are very\ne quality of the\nre going to offer\nwhile at still lower\nare now marked.\nyour needs, and I\nlice CRIB Blank- E\nnes. I\nlire Company, j\nINGSTREE, S. C.\nxatmmn&E e 'Mi k; v.; Ku'pjii.naigig-.Tgi\naHHHl\nInterior of Our Main S\nI Central Warehouse, Op]\nI _\nYUU CAIN'I\nYour Opp\nBeginning Sati\nJ A Full anc\nvertisemi\nI will be I\nI Back Pa|\nIT7^\nIvv c uamiui a\nand Libert Bond:\nment of goods p\nhowever, we will\noffer to accept a\nmore than mark(\nLiberty Bonds at\nj Our Special\ndiscount on all g\nin our three stc\nCentral Wareho\nand Academy sti\nalso Peoples Fur\nI ingway, S. C.\nKingstree Fi\nI Academy Street, Next to Pos\n\n2 wmXM'W Mr l!::raa!i;B!!9ll!; !R!W! eRcaKnUBH^f '.t\nranHHMMHH\nHHHHIHflninr %fl&\nnBHR9^3EPillinEttM^IH\nRR9HHV/^BH9PHPH^^B$^fl|M^^KH^^^^^H gjr.jS\nMKBBBjPBl^^BB^T^-j ^^Pj^B^g^HgBpMBpE^MBII^^^^B a .?<j\nr^ ffl|\nHi\nortunity Sale j\njrday, November 20 I\nl Detailed Ad- f\nent of Which\n?ound on the\nof this Paper\nifford to accept cotton I\ns as heretofore in pay- 1\nmrchased at this sale,\nI continue our former\notton at 2c per pound\nit price day delivered?\nface value on account. v'\nOffer of 33 1-3 per cent\noods means every item j\n)res, main showroom,\nuse, opposite library,\neet, next to postoffice;\nniture Company, Hem?\n\nif I\nirniture Company\ntofflce, KINGSTREE, S. C. I J\nI\n-.^JJ II 'mM","height":"26010","width":"16830"}}
